WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.900
&gt;&gt; Hello. Welcome. It's my great pleasure
to welcome you to Google tonight for the first

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:16.910
talk in conjunction with the third exhibition
in our series of "Digital Art at Google".

00:00:16.910 --> 00:00:22.580
I'm standing in tonight for Josh Mittleman
who should have been here tonight but had

00:00:22.580 --> 00:00:28.220
a building emergency at home so he had to
go home. Josh is an engineer here at Google

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:34.510
who set up this "Digital Art at Google" program
to explore and to encourage collaboration

00:00:34.510 --> 00:00:40.910
between Google and digital artists. So Google's
mission is to organize the world's information

00:00:40.910 --> 00:00:46.489
and make it universally acceptable and useful
and art can be seen as one way to organize

00:00:46.489 --> 00:00:52.719
and access information. And after Google moved
its New York office to Chelsea, Josh looked

00:00:52.719 --> 00:00:57.199
at how Google could reach out to the local
art scene to foster creativity, interaction,

00:00:57.199 --> 00:01:03.839
and innovation. So Josh got in contact with
Nina Colosi who is here tonight and who curates

00:01:03.839 --> 00:01:08.790
The Project Room for New Media and the Streaming
Museum. I invited her to curate this series

00:01:08.790 --> 00:01:13.810
of art exhibitions in the Google offices.
This is the third exhibition that we've had

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:18.290
here this year. So the current exhibition
is "Ancient Stories with Modern Technology"

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:22.800
and we're honored tonight to have one of the
show's artist, Paul Miller, also known as

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:28.890
DJ Spooky. So Paul Miller is a multitalented
artist whose resume I can't possibly do justice

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:33.960
to. As a media artist he has exhibited all
over the world including the Whitney Biennial,

00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:39.390
the Vienna Kunsthalle, and the Venice Architecture
Biennial, and a solo show at Paula Cooper

00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:43.490
Gallery in New York. He's written in many
periodicals including Artforum, the Village

00:01:43.490 --> 00:01:48.220
Voice, and Paper Magazine. He has published
"Rhythm Science", a collection of essays,

00:01:48.220 --> 00:01:54.640
and "Sound Unbound" an anthology of essays
on sound art and multimedia. But he is perhaps

00:01:54.640 --> 00:02:00.250
best known for his constructive DJ Spooky
that Subliminal Kid and has recorded extensively

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:05.990
and collaborated with all manner of musicians
and composers from Pierre Boulez to Yoko Ono.

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:10.989
In this show here at Google, Paul presents
an installation of works inspired by his vision

00:02:10.989 --> 00:02:17.530
for the Vanuatu Pacifica Foundation; an endless
initiative he's asking "Can 21st century technology

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:23.939
supply, support traditional ecological knowledge
in ways that enrich village life and contemporary

00:02:23.939 --> 00:02:29.510
art?" So as one of the artists in this exhibition
and the organizer of the artist talks in the

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:33.390
exhibition series, it's my great pleasure
to introduce Paul Miller. Thank you.

00:02:33.390 --> 00:02:34.390
[applause]

00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:40.050
Paul Miller &gt;&gt; First and foremost, I just
want to say thank you so much for coming out

00:02:40.050 --> 00:02:43.749
tonight and I realize it's always something
to create time in New

00:02:43.749 --> 00:02:48.519
York. I mean in fact that's one of the issues
that was an inspiration for the Vanuatu project,

00:02:48.519 --> 00:02:52.510
this idea of free time. So what I want to
do today is walk you

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:58.010
all through some of the issues that are kind
of resonant with what I'm thinking about with

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:00.549
not only contemporary art but looking at digital
media's

00:03:00.549 --> 00:03:06.700
relationship to what we at the Vanuatu Pacifica
Foundation like to call "traditional ecological

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:10.959
knowledge" (TEK). So one of the things that
I'm really

00:03:10.959 --> 00:03:15.900
thinking about right now as an artist is okay,
in the 21st century how digital media; you

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.180
have this idea of a information based economy
and above all you

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:23.660
have this notion that things are becoming
more and more dematerialized, immaterial and

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:27.510
kind of invisible processes guide most aspects
of the economy, they

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:32.480
guide most aspects of how we think of this
notion of the archive that kind of guides

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:36.709
and gives people structure in terms of everything
from language to

00:03:36.709 --> 00:03:44.190
digital media to how your jet planes are flown
and so on. So one thing that really, how should

00:03:44.190 --> 00:03:48.969
I put this? Like is a core issue for me as
an artist is this

00:03:48.969 --> 00:03:54.260
idea that geography is becoming more and more
abstract so to ground myself as an artist

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:57.420
many of my projects take place in very remote
places which lead me to

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:02.870
this idea of Vanuatu and not only looking
at Vanuatu as a specific geographic place

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:07.000
but as an idea. So what I want to do today
is unpack some of the issues that

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.609
are guiding the Vanuatu Pacifica Foundation
and the Tanna Center for the Arts. But I also

00:04:11.609 --> 00:04:15.030
want to sort of unpack some of the issues
that go through my mind

00:04:15.030 --> 00:04:19.549
when I'm think about contemporary art in the
digital economy and looking at this idea of

00:04:19.549 --> 00:04:24.099
oceanic art and it's relationship to how we
look at different forms of

00:04:24.099 --> 00:04:29.540
cultural production. So behind me you have
a typical example of architecture from the

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:33.740
Vanuatu region. These are kind of large scale
social structures. The

00:04:33.740 --> 00:04:39.150
architecture is built usually by hand and
above all a lot of the material comes from

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:43.379
the region. It's very specific to the area
and you have this idea of a

00:04:43.379 --> 00:04:50.560
kind of sustainable use of materials in the
region. So bamboo, wood, some forms of steel

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:53.990
but most of the material is handmade in a
way that reflects local

00:04:53.990 --> 00:05:00.379
economy, local purposes and so as an artist
that kind of intrigues me in a way because

00:05:00.379 --> 00:05:04.370
how do you think, you know, if I need some
air, I go down to Pearl

00:05:04.370 --> 00:05:08.479
Paint on Canal Street or something like that.
If you are in the middle of a jungle in the

00:05:08.479 --> 00:05:11.800
middle of kind of a different region of the
world, where are your

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:16.120
materials going to come from but the place
that most people would go to, the natural

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:21.380
state of things around you. So at the Vanuatu
Pacifica Foundation, what

00:05:21.380 --> 00:05:26.510
I want to do is say here we have one foot
in this hyper urbanized, media saturated landscape

00:05:26.510 --> 00:05:31.200
of modern America, modern Europe, modern Asia,
and modern Latin

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:36.370
America and Africa, and so on but we also
have one foot in this realm that's kind of

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:42.410
a place of suspended time and Tanna is one
of 83 islands and we're going

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:47.580
to be setting up the Tanna Center for Arts
on this island. So what I want to do is walk

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:53.410
you through some of things that drove me to
Vanuatu or took me to

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:59.289
Vanuatu. Last year I did a project called
Nauru Elegies with a Korean architect named

00:05:59.289 --> 00:06:02.430
Annie K. Kwon. It was a project that was meant
to look a virtual

00:06:02.430 --> 00:06:10.099
economies and it's a intriguing place, Nauru.
It's a place with a totally shattered economy.

00:06:10.099 --> 00:06:15.759
It's a tiny island further north then Vanuatu
and in the early

00:06:15.759 --> 00:06:21.050
90's as the Soviet Union was collapsing, a
group of Russian bankers in what they now

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:24.909
call oligarchs became very clever and very
nimble at shifting around billions

00:06:24.909 --> 00:06:28.720
and billions of dollars out of Russia. And
the Ministry of Finances being looted and

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:31.349
as the Soviet Union was collapsing, hundreds
of billions of dollars

00:06:31.349 --> 00:06:35.310
started to vanish out of Russia and all of
the sudden appear on this small island in

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:40.289
the middle of the South Pacific. So the Russians
were very clever at

00:06:40.289 --> 00:06:45.351
bypassing the normal codes of conduct that
banks had to have in Switzerland or Monaco

00:06:45.351 --> 00:06:49.330
or Luxembourg or the Cayman Islands or the
Isle of Man and most of those

00:06:49.330 --> 00:06:55.320
are what we call tax havens. So the idea of
a tax haven or data haven in our era is a

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:59.360
place that's slightly off the grid. So Nauru,
for me, became a very

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:03.789
compelling place to think about global finance
and I wanted to do this project based on its

00:07:03.789 --> 00:07:06.990
notion of global finance and the virtualization
of banking, which

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:11.350
if you think about it, your credit card status
and your social security number, even if of

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:14.129
course we're here at Google, the digitization
of the landscape

00:07:14.129 --> 00:07:19.720
that goes into GPS maps, all of that means
that the data self, the second self that theoreticians

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:22.469
like Arthur Kroker and Marilouise Kroker like
to call them

00:07:22.469 --> 00:07:28.840
C Theory, the second self. Your data, you
know, the things that define you to the various

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:31.840
digital media that we need to interact with.
These kinds of places

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:38.030
are kind of black holes in the landscape so
Nauru, you have to imagine people being assassinated

00:07:38.030 --> 00:07:41.680
in the streets of Moscow, bankers kind of
running around. The

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:46.319
paper economy was old school at that point
in the early 90's as the Soviet Union collapsed

00:07:46.319 --> 00:07:49.259
like I said earlier; hundreds of billions
of dollars vanishes and

00:07:49.259 --> 00:07:54.470
appears in this small island. So as this kept
happening, as the Soviet Union was in a slow

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:57.759
motion collapse before Boris Yeltsin and so
on. What ends up

00:07:57.759 --> 00:08:03.039
happening is Nauru also achieved a kind of
per capita development situation because of

00:08:03.039 --> 00:08:06.240
the rise of phosphate prices. Now, this island
is made of millions of

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:11.569
years of bird guano, bird shit and in the
middle of the South Pacific it's an agricultural

00:08:11.569 --> 00:08:14.569
wasteland now because it's been mined to the
core and the whole

00:08:14.569 --> 00:08:18.229
island has been stripped bare. So the Russians
on one hand had virtual banking, and then

00:08:18.229 --> 00:08:21.389
other colonial powers like Australia and Britain
and so on had stripped

00:08:21.389 --> 00:08:26.469
the island. So when I arrived last year the
island was this eerie moonscape and what was

00:08:26.469 --> 00:08:29.349
going on is that the Russians had funneled
their money through and

00:08:29.349 --> 00:08:34.460
reappeared in places like UBS in Switzerland
or the Bank of New York in New York. To this

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:37.419
day, people are still being arrested by stuff
that happened in

00:08:37.419 --> 00:08:44.200
Nauru. So the New York Times ran a really
wild article called "The Billion Dollar Shack"

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:49.370
and I'll just pull it up really quick for
you just to give you a

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:50.370
little background on the

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:55.450
[pause]

00:08:55.450 --> 00:09:03.680
and what ends up going on in this, oops, let's
go back. What ends up happening in this kind

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:05.610
of island situation is that at

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:12.050
one point there became more corporations on
the island then there were people, and what's

00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:14.070
really fascinating with that to me as an artist
is that

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:18.371
corporations are considered people but what
happens with this notion of virtual banking

00:09:18.371 --> 00:09:21.050
is that all you need is an address and if
you're looking at Enron, if

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:25.250
you're looking at the banking crisis of 2008,
people play with geography, they play with

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:28.290
how many represents certain kind of value.
But to me what's

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:35.850
interesting is that money isn't really a reflection
of value per se. It's about the notions of

00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:38.899
social use of materials and when I say materials
we're looking

00:09:38.899 --> 00:09:44.920
at electronic and digital media materials.
So, alright, you're in the middle of the South

00:09:44.920 --> 00:09:47.880
Pacific and you show up on this island where
all these corporations

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:52.010
that were virtual financial institutions,
what they call shell corporations, had been

00:09:52.010 --> 00:09:56.910
made. And also you're realizing that the island
is stunningly poor and

00:09:56.910 --> 00:10:00.930
that the place is completely strip mined and
bare. And so it's a desert in the middle of

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:04.200
this beautiful region of the South Pacific
because of the collision of

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:08.899
the physical infrastructure of the mining
versus the virtual banking that happened from

00:10:08.899 --> 00:10:14.510
Moscow straight through. So there's this one
place on the island

00:10:14.510 --> 00:10:18.670
where there was a server that the Russians
used to funnel all the money through and Nauru

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:21.280
started popping up in all these kind of science
fiction books by

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:26.380
people like William Gibson, people like Bruce
Sterling or Neal Stephenson because a lot

00:10:26.380 --> 00:10:30.779
of the science fiction had heard about this
island as this bizarre

00:10:30.779 --> 00:10:35.690
economic black hole in the global system.
So it became a place where like gangster bankers

00:10:35.690 --> 00:10:38.170
would park their money and then it would disappear,
or if you were a

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:41.389
major arms dealer and you needed to funnel
a couple of billion dollars to like a warlord

00:10:41.389 --> 00:10:45.320
in Angola, you know, the money would go through
Nauru. And right now

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:50.710
in fact, because of the Iraq war and I'm going
to get back on topic in a second about Vanuatu

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:53.351
but because of the Iraq War for example you
can get a Nauru

00:10:53.351 --> 00:10:58.240
passport because most of the industrialized
nations have signed what they called anti-mercenary

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:01.380
laws so if you need to get a citizenship of
a virtual place

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:05.480
you get a Nauru passport, you then reapply
to Blackwater Security, and the next thing

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:09.329
you know you're in Iraq so there you go. So
this is an ongoing idea of

00:11:09.329 --> 00:11:14.890
a virtual economy and one of the funny things
about money is it's like energy, it never

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:19.860
really vanishes, it goes someplace. So in
2008 when a lot of the US's

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:23.410
money sort of went up in smoke because of
all of the derivatives markets, futures markets,

00:11:23.410 --> 00:11:28.730
what they call CDO, credit default swaps,
all this kind of virtual

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:33.339
finance and the Russians had already experienced
something quirkily similar to that in the

00:11:33.339 --> 00:11:36.790
beginning of the 90's with the fall of the
Soviet banking system.

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:42.519
So, to make a long story short, I'm an artist,
I'm a writer, I'm somewhat interested in music

00:11:42.519 --> 00:11:45.020
not just music but music as information. It's
something that

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:50.880
reflects social values through the prism of
digital media. So the reason I'm having this

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:53.430
idea of a billion dollar shack in the middle
of the island in the

00:11:53.430 --> 00:11:58.880
South Pacific is that this became an ideal
of dystopia. So let me just show you some

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:04.639
of the ruins of the phosphate corporations.
All of the island is

00:12:04.639 --> 00:12:08.600
collapsing right now. It's kind of got all
these kind of warning signs, all the buildings

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:11.880
are in slow motion collapse, it looks like
a nuclear bomb has gone

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:18.581
off and eerily enough, all of the structures
are just rusted and collapsing and the notion

00:12:18.581 --> 00:12:22.360
of global finance that drove the phosphate
mining and also drove, on the other hand,

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:26.730
the virtual economy, all of that has departed
from the island kind of like locusts or something

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:28.829
that just came in and took over, put up

00:12:28.829 --> 00:12:34.420
all these structures and buildings, and then
just vanished. So that's why people like William

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:36.820
Gibson and Bruce Sterling, the cyber punk
writers, are very

00:12:36.820 --> 00:12:43.240
interested in it. So Annie K. Kwon's architecture
reflected this idea of what she called Hypsographic

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.959
Architecture and if you couldn't find a better
metaphor

00:12:45.959 --> 00:12:49.350
for globalization right now. The island is
actually sinking as well so

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:50.350
[chuckle]

00:12:50.350 --> 00:12:55.019
you have a collapsed economy, a strip mine
place that's been made into an

00:12:55.019 --> 00:12:59.420
eerie ghost island and at the same time the
waters are rising so I was like hey, as an

00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:06.079
artist, this is a wild place. Let's go, let's
go to Nauru. So Vanuatu

00:13:06.079 --> 00:13:10.769
represents another extreme which is very much
considered what they call a utopian model.

00:13:10.769 --> 00:13:13.530
So what I want to do before I get into utopias
is to think about

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:18.139
this idea of what I like to call the "gift
economy". So to invoke that what I'd like

00:13:18.139 --> 00:13:20.970
to do is give away a whole bunch of music.
Can I ask if you can just

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:26.520
take some of these and pass them to other
people? Alright. So take one and pass it along

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.790
and if there's not enough, there's plenty
of CD's I brought with me.

00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:34.860
I'll leave some up here just in case. If you
are in the back and you don't get one, there's

00:13:34.860 --> 00:13:39.149
plenty here. So what I want to do is invoke
this notion of what

00:13:39.149 --> 00:13:43.389
the anthropologist Marcel Mauss liked to call
the "gift economy" because he was studying

00:13:43.389 --> 00:13:46.920
American Indians and looking at how certain
cultures came up with

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:51.839
what they call potlatch and that was the opposite
of the normal capitalist model of scarcity.

00:13:51.839 --> 00:13:55.079
In fact, you're supposed to achieve social
status and achieve

00:13:55.079 --> 00:14:00.329
this idea of parody with your peers by giving
away things. So the more you gave in certain

00:14:00.329 --> 00:14:04.680
societies and cultures, the more you achieve
social status. So the

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:08.759
network economy is a similar thing. If you're
a blogger, if you're someone who accumulates

00:14:08.759 --> 00:14:12.450
information, you achieve social status by
creating a value of

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:17.120
information. A very nuanced and very ambiguous
and very interesting way of thinking about

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:21.319
reconstituting value in a digital economy.
So the "gift economy"

00:14:21.319 --> 00:14:26.500
overlaps with the net. Now I hope I'm not
losing you all in this but I'm thinking much

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:30.600
more about this idea of the network effect
which sometimes - say for

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:34.699
example one website comes along and just all
of the sudden becomes viral and so big very

00:14:34.699 --> 00:14:38.820
quickly. That's what economists like to call
a network effect.

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:44.660
In the arts, say for example Andy Warhol's
brand, created value much more then any specific

00:14:44.660 --> 00:14:47.240
practice because he was branded figure and
the more people heard

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:51.481
about the work, the more it accumulated value
so the same thing happened with Facebook or

00:14:51.481 --> 00:14:54.560
Google or any of these kind of things. You're
looking at an overlap

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:59.100
of social systems then becoming quantized
and being able to have metrics to measure

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:05.250
that value and it's about the buzz of something.
So Nauru versus Vanuatu;

00:15:05.250 --> 00:15:11.889
utopia versus dystopia; the idea of how we
navigate network systems socially. So in our

00:15:11.889 --> 00:15:14.570
culture in the US, we are now really, really,
really everyone is

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:18.310
obsessed with social networks right now but
in other cultures we are actually kind of

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:21.060
catching up to them; a small village where
everyone knows everyone and

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:26.260
has certain forms of trade and communication;
a different way of thinking about the idea

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:29.050
of how you accumulate value and social prestige;
these are things

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:34.759
that I was thinking about when I arrived in
Vanuatu. So me and Annie left Nauru, went

00:15:34.759 --> 00:15:38.129
to Australia, hung out in Australia for a
moment, and then went to

00:15:38.129 --> 00:15:42.700
Vanuatu. Vanuatu was meant to be the opposite
of Nauru. So when you see this ghost island

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:43.700
that's got, it's been strip mined. You can
see it's almost like a

00:15:43.700 --> 00:15:49.160
cancer cell that's spread through the island
and stripped away all the value and then you

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:52.990
see all those structures collapsing. Let's
got to Vanuatu and see

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:59.589
something very different. So what I want to
do before I show you more images is invoke

00:15:59.589 --> 00:16:04.079
another situation which is the idea of the
"mix". I've been working

00:16:04.079 --> 00:16:09.850
with Apple and Musicsoft Arts and I have the
DJ Spooky iPhone app and iPad app, and with

