00:25:58.309 --> 00:26:03.780
Russia is kind of Wild West. It's definitely
a fun spot. So I've

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:08.210
seen a lot and been in a lot of radically
different continents but the glue that holds

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:12.510
all this together is digital media. I'm a
music producer and I'm an

00:26:12.510 --> 00:26:18.279
artist that looks at digital media as a kind
of dematerialized tool. So what I want to

00:26:18.279 --> 00:26:22.049
do tonight is when you see this "Meet The
Natives", to me it's

00:26:22.049 --> 00:26:25.990
appalling, it's bizarre, it's paradoxical
much in the same way the D.W. Griffith's "Birth

00:26:25.990 --> 00:26:29.820
of a Nation" had white people in blackface
kind of representing

00:26:29.820 --> 00:26:33.660
this notion of you know, I'm sure the Tea
Party is probably watching it now, right?

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:38.620
But when you think about digital media, globalization,
and all these

00:26:38.620 --> 00:26:43.600
issues that face artists in any context anywhere
on the planet. Vanuatu and Tanna specifically

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:47.470
is a very unique places because it has this
utopian vision of

00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:52.490
something that's a very pristine and beautiful
and remote place. It kind of has this at the

00:26:52.490 --> 00:26:55.960
edge of the known world feel to it and that's
why I went since

00:26:55.960 --> 00:27:00.701
timelessness, sense of being out of the media
kind of maelstrom, and hitting the reset button

00:27:00.701 --> 00:27:04.300
on the idea of creativity. So I took a studio
with me and I

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:09.510
went to several of the main villages and I
ended up hanging out and I noticed they loved

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:12.640
radio, and there was only a couple kind of
places on the island

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:18.080
where people could really hang out and listen
to music in a large show context. So my girlfriend

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:22.020
Annie, or ex-girlfriend, walked around and
it was interesting

00:27:22.020 --> 00:27:28.200
because we kept being looked at. We were very
different and Annie is Korean and I'm African-American

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:31.309
and us walking around was just kind of novelty
for the

00:27:31.309 --> 00:27:34.190
indigenous people. They are like "Who are
these guys?" because usually the quote on

00:27:34.190 --> 00:27:37.510
quote "tourists" that come to Tanna are there
to see this volcano. They

00:27:37.510 --> 00:27:42.600
come in for a day and it's usually some beefy
people from Australia who sit and lounge and

00:27:42.600 --> 00:27:46.350
drink at this one resort on the island and
then leave. So they

00:27:46.350 --> 00:27:50.340
don't interact, they don't hang out, they
just come see this crazy volcano and leave.

00:27:50.340 --> 00:27:54.090
So me and Annie ended up hanging out there.
We were planning on staying

00:27:54.090 --> 00:27:57.510
there for one week and we ended up staying
for four weeks. I went swimming every day

00:27:57.510 --> 00:28:02.539
and had fresh fish every day. I loved walking
and I walked around. So

00:28:02.539 --> 00:28:06.330
what I want to do is contextualize this, not
only from the view point of why as an artist

00:28:06.330 --> 00:28:10.260
I fell in love with this beautiful region
but thinking about in an arts

00:28:10.260 --> 00:28:15.660
context. Now, there's a couple of other artists
that are doing really interesting kind of

00:28:15.660 --> 00:28:21.010
projects about environmental issues and so
on and one is a project

00:28:21.010 --> 00:28:28.049
that Rirkrit Tiravanija is doing and that's
called the Land Project. This is in Thailand

00:28:28.049 --> 00:28:32.070
and what he's doing is reclaiming a series
of fields and setting up

00:28:32.070 --> 00:28:39.000
a series of art projects around rice and exchange
and everyone who participates in the project

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.930
gets their share of rice of what they put
in. So it's very

00:28:41.930 --> 00:28:46.919
specific to thinking about environmental issues
and indigenous populations but it's done by

00:28:46.919 --> 00:28:50.861
Thai artists in Thailand. So although Rirkrit
lives in New York,

00:28:50.861 --> 00:28:57.580
the project is initiated by someone is indigenous
to that culture. Now what we're going to be

00:28:57.580 --> 00:29:00.590
doing with the Tanna Center for the Arts is
a kind of exchange

00:29:00.590 --> 00:29:05.570
mechanism. It's going to be a forum for saying,
"Hey, wait a second. Let's think about this

00:29:05.570 --> 00:29:09.640
from the viewpoint of we have something to
learn from these

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:15.919
people". Now there's this group of economists
that have come up with what they call the

00:29:15.919 --> 00:29:20.330
New Economic forum or foundation and Vanuatu
has been consistently,

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:25.260
over the last several years, although it's
not this year because they had a whole recreatement

00:29:25.260 --> 00:29:29.140
of criteria of judgment and the economics
of what make it

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:34.760
happy. So what I'm talking about now is production
values, social networks, and stuff like that.

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:39.130
The New Economic Foundation set up this system
for measuring

00:29:39.130 --> 00:29:43.320
happiness. Now, Vanuatu, whenever you think
about this idea of the native, remember I

00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:48.080
was showing you earlier "Meet The Natives"
and the smiling guys from

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:52.980
Tanna and they're meant to be happy and relaxed
and primitive in the middle of like this complex,

00:29:52.980 --> 00:29:57.130
crazy society called the English or England.
So the West

00:29:57.130 --> 00:30:00.940
always like to think about this idea of the
national state of the other. You know, if

00:30:00.940 --> 00:30:04.090
you look at "Heart of Darkness" or if you
look at certain other books

00:30:04.090 --> 00:30:08.570
in the literature of colonialism, going native
and hanging out with the indigenous people,

00:30:08.570 --> 00:30:11.220
guess what, it's still with us. Look at the
movie "Avatar", right?

00:30:11.220 --> 00:30:16.740
The white guy from the complex society goes
to this beautiful tropical planet and becomes

00:30:16.740 --> 00:30:19.641
blue and all of the sudden he likes, "Hey,
forget the corporation.

00:30:19.641 --> 00:30:24.640
I'm going to lead the native people to rebel",
right? It's exactly like Tarzan and so on.

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:29.049
We've seen this one before. So when you think
about "Avatar" and

00:30:29.049 --> 00:30:35.289
the idea of going native and so on, the other,
if you look at the history of philosophy and

00:30:35.289 --> 00:30:37.789
again philosophy of technology here. Rousseau,
Voltaire, you know?

00:30:37.789 --> 00:30:41.830
There's lot of theoreticians that thought
about indigenous people as the pure ones.

00:30:41.830 --> 00:30:46.130
The ones who somehow avoided the complex corruption
of our crazy

00:30:46.130 --> 00:30:50.059
technological advanced society. So I'm intrigued
with turning that upside down and saying,

00:30:50.059 --> 00:30:54.070
"Wait a second. What would happen if we said
this is a complex

00:30:54.070 --> 00:30:58.470
society?" They have problems of their own.
They have a whole situation where we're coming

00:30:58.470 --> 00:31:02.220
in as aliens, you know? But the fun part about
it for me as an

00:31:02.220 --> 00:31:07.330
artist was that music was the glue. So when
I ended up meeting some of the people from

00:31:07.330 --> 00:31:10.090
the island which is you know people were staring,
they were curious.

00:31:10.090 --> 00:31:14.090
They saw an African-American guy and a Korean
woman walking around. First and foremost,

00:31:14.090 --> 00:31:18.360
the foreigners never walk. They always are
usually in a car and me

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:21.669
and Annie walking around and actually swimming.
Nobody was swimming even though there were

00:31:21.669 --> 00:31:24.850
these beautiful, stunningly beautiful coral
reefs. Me and her would

00:31:24.850 --> 00:31:28.490
swim for hours and hours and they were like,
"Who are these foreigners that actually like

00:31:28.490 --> 00:31:32.260
to swim", you know? It was, I mean, you'd
walked down a stunningly

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:35.350
beautiful beach for hours and not bump into
another person which for me is great being

00:31:35.350 --> 00:31:40.080
from New York, right? Try doing that on the
E Train or something else.

00:31:40.080 --> 00:31:46.260
There's always too many people all the time.
So when I think about the complexity of an

00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:49.590
artist leaving New York and going to this
beautiful island, it's not

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:54.260
about Aldous Huxley. It's not about Rousseau
and the idea of that natural state of natural

00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:57.399
man. What I'm saying is that these are complex
societies that I

00:31:57.399 --> 00:32:01.960
have to figure out if I'm going to be participating
in any way, shape, or form in our own culture.

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:04.820
It's a mirror, you know? Sometimes one of
my favorite

00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:09.909
writers is a gentleman by the name of Pico
Iyer. He writes about the philosophy of travel.

00:32:09.909 --> 00:32:13.159
And as a deejay whose deejayed all over the
world and again, in a

00:32:13.159 --> 00:32:17.690
digital media context, I'm really intrigued
at that. So right now I'm at this point where

00:32:17.690 --> 00:32:21.309
I feel like the cities that we've built are,
they are poorly

00:32:21.309 --> 00:32:25.799
structured for our modern life. Most American
cities are based on the grid. The logic of

00:32:25.799 --> 00:32:29.210
the grid conditions and contextualizes our
sense of space and time.

00:32:29.210 --> 00:32:34.360
If you look at Detriot from above to Chicago,
New York, Washington D.C., the American logic

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:38.799
of the grid has made us have a sense of compression
and if you

00:32:38.799 --> 00:32:42.030
think about the electronic music that comes
out of the grid, this is something I'm very

00:32:42.030 --> 00:32:45.850
intrigued with as well. It's like this notion
of the orthogonal logic

00:32:45.850 --> 00:32:51.830
of our time. I'll show a quick example. I'm
working on my next couple of projects based

00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:55.169
on Stephen Wolfram who is a really renowned
mathematician. He has this

00:32:55.169 --> 00:33:00.659
book called "Mathematica" that does analysis
of natural forms as algorithmic states. So

00:33:00.659 --> 00:33:04.019
say for example, I'll give you one example
because I know this

00:33:04.019 --> 00:33:09.350
conversation would feel like Vanuatu, Nauru,
economics, happiness, crazy New York, you

00:33:09.350 --> 00:33:13.340
know? So I'm trying to think of it as a collage
lecture. So what

00:33:13.340 --> 00:33:17.760
you're seeing behind me are various natural
forms that have a very mathematical, very

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:22.490
algorithmic kind of context. Say the most
obvious example is this

00:33:22.490 --> 00:33:26.800
snowflake, right? You see a snowflake. They
are hexagon and there's a mathematical equation

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:29.289
that a gentleman by the name of Johannes Kepler
who was a really

00:33:29.289 --> 00:33:38.850
renowned physicist from the 16th or 17th century,
1642 I believe or something like that. So

00:33:38.850 --> 00:33:41.930
every snowflake is unique because it's precisely
the condition and

00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:46.060
context that make it slightly different but
there's a rule based structure under it. So

00:33:46.060 --> 00:33:51.270
a snowflake is hexagon which means it has
a unique form but it also

00:33:51.270 --> 00:33:55.250
has a unique relationship to that form each
time it manifests. So if you're ever walking

00:33:55.250 --> 00:33:58.700
through a snowstorm you're actually being
bombarded with unique

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:04.600
instances of weather patterns. Now, considering
we're here at Google, weather patterns are

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:06.600
some of the most complex things that human
beings have ever tried

00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:12.230
to model. So you need a super computer system
to understand the wind. You need a massive

00:34:12.230 --> 00:34:16.751
computational logic just to understand ocean
currents. So now if you

00:34:16.751 --> 00:34:23.050
apply that model to native beings and economics
we're placed in this context where most of

00:34:23.050 --> 00:34:26.550
modern economics is just a belief system and
we still are trying

00:34:26.550 --> 00:34:31.900
to figure this stuff out. There's people like
Milton Friedman, John Maynard Keynes; very

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:34.370
few people would have been able to understand
the complexity of the

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:41.750
2008 economic crisis and meltdown but you
know at the end of the day when you think

00:34:41.750 --> 00:34:44.750
about economics, it's about how people structure
themselves in

00:34:44.750 --> 00:34:49.450
relationship to society. So the reason I brought
up the New Economic Foundation earlier is

00:34:49.450 --> 00:34:53.590
that they rated Vanuatu through the Happy
Planet Index and they

00:34:53.590 --> 00:34:57.590
were ripping on this from the Tanna point
of view here because I'm fascinated with this

00:34:57.590 --> 00:35:00.790
idea of free time and free space. And as a
New Yorker those are two

00:35:00.790 --> 00:35:05.310
very scarce things that we inhabit. I mean,
if you think about the idea that most people

00:35:05.310 --> 00:35:07.990
are running around paying their credit card
bill or having to deal

00:35:07.990 --> 00:35:11.840
with all the different kinds of micro finance,
micro credit you know, we might as well call

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:14.270
it a plantation system at this point. We are
just all like

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:19.920
micro serfs like Douglas Cooper in his book,
right? So the Happy Planet Index tries to

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:23.230
understand gross domestic product through
other metrics, through other

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:28.470
ways of measuring productivity. So the GDP,
gross domestic product, is something that

00:35:28.470 --> 00:35:32.510
basically is about 19 century models being
applied to a 21st century

00:35:32.510 --> 00:35:38.290
economy, they don't work. So the happiness
index, it's kind of a new way of looking at

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:42.460
how people product material value but also
psychological value. If

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:46.360
there's anything, if you look at the root
word of credit which is something I love to

00:35:46.360 --> 00:35:48.930
point out to economists, it just simply means
credere which is the

00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:54.200
Latin term for believe. So Adam Smith had
a great phrase where he said, "All money is

00:35:54.200 --> 00:35:58.571
just a matter of belief." So imagine if you're
on an island and the

00:35:58.571 --> 00:36:03.110
chief of a certain region approaches you which
is a gentleman by the name of Isso Kapum and

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:06.560
his father Jack Kapum. They are walking down
a dirt road like me

00:36:06.560 --> 00:36:10.400
and Annie were doing one time and we ended
up bumping into these two gentleman and we

00:36:10.400 --> 00:36:12.760
got into a long conversation about why are
you here

00:36:12.760 --> 00:36:14.840
[laughs]

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:18.080
and I majored in philosophy and French literature.
I don't know if anybody out there knows Bowdoin

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:22.370
College but Bowdoin is one of the Little Ivies.
We are very

00:36:22.370 --> 00:36:28.230
competitive with Harvard, you know? But, so,
I was very philosophical about this when I

00:36:28.230 --> 00:36:31.050
meant these two gentleman and I said, "You
know, I have some mix CD's.

00:36:31.050 --> 00:36:35.700
I keep hearing reggae blasting out of these
cars. Why don't you guys listen to old school

00:36:35.700 --> 00:36:39.300
reggae and not the commercial, kind of crappy
stuff?" It's a long

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:43.170
story. I work with Trojan Records which is
a legendary Jamaican record label and in London

00:36:43.170 --> 00:36:46.110
a couple of years ago they gave me access
to a huge warehouse of

00:36:46.110 --> 00:36:51.700
old 45 vinyl. So I collect like, this is when
Bob Marley was 18 for example and he's singing

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:55.130
great stuff or Lee "Scratch" Perry so I always
carry a couple of

00:36:55.130 --> 00:37:00.070
CD's with me as you guys didn't notice that,
right? So I pulled the "gift economy" on them.

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:03.790
I pull out a mix CD of old school reggae,
give it to them, and

00:37:03.790 --> 00:37:07.600
then a couple, like we ended up staying like
a lot longer then we were planning because

00:37:07.600 --> 00:37:09.990
we didn't feel like going back to New York.
A couple of days later

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:13.570
we started hearing old school reggae coming
from a couple of different places and I realized

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:15.619
that people had made copies of the mix and
were passing it

00:37:15.619 --> 00:37:21.660
around. What ended up happening is the music
became a kind of fun way of saying this is

00:37:21.660 --> 00:37:26.240
a "gift economy" from a New Yorker to you.
And I noticed that people,

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:30.430
even to this day, the last time I went back
to Vanuatu I heard some of the mixed I had

00:37:30.430 --> 00:37:35.330
made being played around the island so that
was a real interesting

00:37:35.330 --> 00:37:40.420
thing, turning upside down the idea of music
and value, music and economy, and saying that

00:37:40.420 --> 00:37:43.470
the gift which people like Lewis Hyde and
Marcel Mauss write about

00:37:43.470 --> 00:37:48.770
very eloquently. The gift is what broke the
ice. So I'm telling you guys a story here.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:51.750
I mean, I could easily, because we're at Google,
I could get into

00:37:51.750 --> 00:37:55.250
hardcore theory speak about the notion of
the metrics of how you measure happiness and

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:58.691
thinking about the notion of how you quantify
this idea of a gift to

00:37:58.691 --> 00:38:03.270
someone else because it creates a relationship
and there's a dynamic logic tree that actually

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:07.530
applies to how people pass information between
people. But

00:38:07.530 --> 00:38:11.310
that's the term of the gentleman by the name
of Norbert Wiener, if anybody out there has

00:38:11.310 --> 00:38:13.381
ever heard of cybernetic theory or information
theory and exchange

00:38:13.381 --> 00:38:20.550
mechanisms and so on, so I'll leave that for
another lecture. So when I started my discussion

00:38:20.550 --> 00:38:23.600
about playing you guys "Meet The Natives",
these are people who

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:30.380
are inhabiting a very complex space and culture
and I'm fascinated with that because precisely

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:37.510
in the West we might have actually tried to
catch up to them.

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:41.520
The reason I'm thinking about this as an artist
is not only because we're setting up a contemporary

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:44.590
art center but the way we're trying to kind
of look at

00:38:44.590 --> 00:38:50.560
graphic design. I just did a project called
"Green Patriot" with a gentleman by the name

00:38:50.560 --> 00:38:55.180
of Shep Fairey who did the Obama "Hope" poster.
We did this project

00:38:55.180 --> 00:39:00.390
looking at green graphic design and then you
realize if you go to a place like Tanna, they've

00:39:00.390 --> 00:39:03.470
incorporated the idea of sustainability into
the very clothing.

00:39:03.470 --> 00:39:07.460
You have people wearing grass skirts and they're
also looking at this idea of sustainability

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:10.650
but they also have problems of their own.
They have various

00:39:10.650 --> 00:39:17.950
medical issues, various issues with like pollution
and composting and so on. So in the US we

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:20.870
have problems but at the same time these are
issues that we need

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:26.270
to understand through the prism of art and
that's where I think the Vanuatu Project is

00:39:26.270 --> 00:39:29.720
really going to be all about this idea of
carbon negative structures,

00:39:29.720 --> 00:39:35.180
carbon negative architecture, and above all
carbon negative senses of social space. How

00:39:35.180 --> 00:39:40.240
do we create this idea of hitting the reset
button on creativity by

00:39:40.240 --> 00:39:45.360
giving people free space and free time? So
what I'm going to be looking at is bamboo

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:49.040
architecture as a main motif for the project
and thinking about using

00:39:49.040 --> 00:39:52.340
local materials in the same way, like I was
saying earlier, the indigenous people already

00:39:52.340 --> 00:39:57.420
are doing but perhaps bringing a little bit
of our tech may and our

00:39:57.420 --> 00:40:05.010
digital media into collision with theirs.
So Tanna is at a certain kind of crossroads.

00:40:05.010 --> 00:40:09.540
The oceanic culture, the Melanesian culture
that it comes from is

00:40:09.540 --> 00:40:13.940
under a kind of ebb and flow. People are leaving
the smaller islands and going to the larger

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:16.350
islands because in the same way that in the
US, and in most

00:40:16.350 --> 00:40:20.570
countries of the world, young people are leaving
the countryside and going to the big city.

00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:23.340
Now, that kind of brain drain is something
that inspired Jack

00:40:23.340 --> 00:40:29.360
Kapum and Isso Kapum to approach us to think
about, "Wait a second, maybe we can do an

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:31.990
experiment together. Maybe we can figure out
a way to get the young

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:37.020
people on the island to stay." So the music
that I gave them started being copied and

00:40:37.020 --> 00:40:40.150
passed around. People realized that there
was a kind of relationship

00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:44.490
between you know, in New York we would just
call it old school, you know? Like old school

00:40:44.490 --> 00:40:47.280
reggae and old school hip-hop and when they
were hearing all

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:50.490
this new digital music coming out of their
cell phones. We were there, for example, when

00:40:50.490 --> 00:40:53.950
the first cell phone network was made on the
island. They realized

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:57.870
they liked some of the older stuff and people
were passing that around so it became part

00:40:57.870 --> 00:41:03.040
of the "gift economy". Again, what I was invoking
earlier. So I made

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:06.790
the logo for the project. I'm a graphic designer
and I'm also thinking about relationships

00:41:06.790 --> 00:41:10.700
to memory. I'm thinking about how sampling
is a kind of "gift

00:41:10.700 --> 00:41:14.560
economy" in it's own right where you're editing
memories and transforming sounds from this

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:18.070
idea of a shareware culture but what happens
when that becomes

00:41:18.070 --> 00:41:24.160
dematerialized? What happens when an artist
says, "Let's hit the reset button". So today

00:41:24.160 --> 00:41:28.720
I stand in front of you working with people
like Islandsfirst.org,

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:37.890
umm, let me just call everything up first.
Umm, and they're our fiscal sponsor for the

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:41.120
Tanna Center for the Arts and the Vanuatu
Pacifica Foundation

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:49.140
precisely because we view this idea of collaboration
and sharing as a basic principle of the foundation.

00:41:49.140 --> 00:41:53.480
The idea, Manhattan itself is an island. I
mean,

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:57.870
don't be fooled. We are just a huge, concrete,
super imposition to what had essentially been

00:41:57.870 --> 00:42:06.290
a very beautiful place. So island to island,
Manhattan to Tanna; I'm thinking a lot more

00:42:06.290 --> 00:42:11.170
about this idea of how free space and free
time can allow artists, writers, musicians

00:42:11.170 --> 00:42:14.110
to actually kind of get a new way of dealing

00:42:14.110 --> 00:42:18.490
with not only their own work but saying, "Let's
look at the future here. Let's think about

00:42:18.490 --> 00:42:21.630
the next twenty years, the next thirty years."
And when happens

00:42:21.630 --> 00:42:26.410
when you're looking at places like Macdowell
Colony or when you're looking at Yaddo Colony.

00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:30.310
You have to imagine that these are places
that are well funded

00:42:30.310 --> 00:42:35.450
and have had a tremendous amount of backing.
The Tanna Center for the Arts and the Vanuatu

00:42:35.450 --> 00:42:37.870
Pacifica Foundation are crowd sourced from
the ground up. We

00:42:37.870 --> 00:42:43.180
started everything off from a two starter
campaign and in fact we had, we're just at

00:42:43.180 --> 00:42:47.380
the edge of it so if people out there want
to donate, please do. It's

00:42:47.380 --> 00:42:51.710
fully tax deductible. But the whole notion
of an outsourced arts center that's turned

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:56.510
into this idea that's upside down. We don't
have the normal patron

00:42:56.510 --> 00:43:01.811
system and we don't need the normal grant
kind of foundational stuff going on. The whole

00:43:01.811 --> 00:43:04.630
notion is that this is going to be a crowd
sourced initiative based

00:43:04.630 --> 00:43:09.310
on substantiality in the arts and want to
get people to think about what happens when

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:12.421
you leave your comfort zone. What happens
when you hit the reset button?

00:43:12.421 --> 00:43:16.870
Not only on the creative process in general
but getting people to just say this is something

00:43:16.870 --> 00:43:20.000
that should be celebrated. So the foundation
is going to be an

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:25.030
enabler, a foundation, a platform. We're going
to be inviting artists, writers, composers,

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:28.381
theoreticians out to the island to hang out
but not just hang out

00:43:28.381 --> 00:43:33.440
like sitting on a beach someplace but to see
how the indigenous population works and above

00:43:33.440 --> 00:43:37.420
all to say this is a dialogue, it's a conversation,
it's a Socratic

00:43:37.420 --> 00:43:42.860
situation. I love this idea. It's a long story.
I majored in philosophy and French literature

00:43:42.860 --> 00:43:46.210
and to go back to what I was saying with William
Gibson earlier

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:52.520
is a great phrase where he says, "The future
is already here. It's just unevenly distributed."

00:43:52.520 --> 00:43:55.010
And I'm going to show a quick example of some
of my artwork

00:43:55.010 --> 00:44:03.410
for a second just to give you an idea of why
I enjoy that kind of paradox. When you think

00:44:03.410 --> 00:44:06.850
about digital literacy, one of the first things
that comes to mind

00:44:06.850 --> 00:44:14.440
is that digital is a specifically kind of
mathematical formula. In fact, one could argue

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:18.000
that analog systems are actually far more
complex so the human eye

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:22.960
and the human ear are complex information
gathering systems. Behind me you have a very

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:26.510
famous photograph from Georges Melies who
popularized what we like to

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:31.270
call stop motion photography. So this is the
cover of "Scientific American" in 1915. What

00:44:31.270 --> 00:44:33.840
you're seeing is something that human beings
have not been able to

00:44:33.840 --> 00:44:39.080
see before. Motion had been cut up and captured
into small fragments so when you hear a digital

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:42.070
voice coming out your cell phone, your voice
has also been

00:44:42.070 --> 00:44:46.240
carved up into small data packets, sent through
a network, and someone else has to then hear

00:44:46.240 --> 00:44:49.120
it but a computer compiles those data packets
and makes it

00:44:49.120 --> 00:44:55.540
become a coherent signal. So the human eye
is not digital. We are analog viewers, analog

00:44:55.540 --> 00:44:58.870
listeners. The brain operates with a deep
degree of complexity and

00:44:58.870 --> 00:45:04.010
nuance and layers. But I love this photograph
precisely because it's kind of at the edge

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:08.830
of paradox. In 1915, this was a wild new statement
about visuality. So

00:45:08.830 --> 00:45:14.650
if we fast forward to 2010, how do we read
these new forms of data? How do we think about

00:45:14.650 --> 00:45:18.120
the way human beings structure and exchange
information and

00:45:18.120 --> 00:45:22.260
content? By the way, if you can't read that,
which probably most of you are not computers

00:45:22.260 --> 00:45:28.400
and you can't, it's the URL for the Vanuatu
Pacifica Foundation.

00:45:28.400 --> 00:45:33.090
So my QR prints as part of this exhibition
were kind of data packets that I wanted to

00:45:33.090 --> 00:45:36.190
set up. If you go up to the prints out in
front of here and you put

00:45:36.190 --> 00:45:39.680
your cell phone up to them, they'll take you
to the Vanuatu Pacifica site, they'll take

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:43.170
you to the YouTube clips and video channel,
and above all they're

00:45:43.170 --> 00:45:48.980
going to be using your cell phone as a portal
into this different world of Tanna time. So

00:45:48.980 --> 00:45:51.460
the Vanuatu Pacifica Foundation is looking
at different forms of

00:45:51.460 --> 00:45:56.270
digital literacy from the viewpoint of ancient
to the future, much in the same way as this

00:45:56.270 --> 00:45:59.050
exhibition is. We are saying that, like William
Gibson, the future

00:45:59.050 --> 00:46:04.110
is already here, it's just unevenly distributed
but above all as artists, writers, and musicians

00:46:04.110 --> 00:46:07.010
I think we have a responsibility to get people
free space to

00:46:07.010 --> 00:46:11.020
re-imagine the near future because - well,
after just coming back from the North Pole

00:46:11.020 --> 00:46:17.200
I can tell you it looks pretty grim. I spent
four weeks carrying a

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:20.870
studio around the North Pole. I don't know
if you can see since it's pretty dark, and

00:46:20.870 --> 00:46:23.801
the idea was to give to several of the main
ice fields and do what I

00:46:23.801 --> 00:46:29.400
like to call acoustic portraits of ice; all
of this is on my website by the way. So I

00:46:29.400 --> 00:46:32.680
carried a studio around and this is going
to be a small group of string

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:37.460
quartet works and the year before that I went
to the South Pole. I went to Antarctica for

00:46:37.460 --> 00:46:41.230
four weeks and did a serious of acoustic portraits
of ice as well. So

00:46:41.230 --> 00:46:46.860
sitting around just kind of literally for
hours and hours walking through huge ice fields,

00:46:46.860 --> 00:46:50.530
I was able to see, regretfully the screens
are a little bit dark

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:55.061
but these are massive, massive ice boulders
that had just shattered off of these huge

00:46:55.061 --> 00:47:00.650
glaciers. Now this is going to be a picture
book, it's my next book and

00:47:00.650 --> 00:47:05.560
this is going to be a series of photo portraits
mixed with sort of eco statements and analysis

00:47:05.560 --> 00:47:08.870
of the quantum physics of ice. If anyone out
there knows

00:47:08.870 --> 00:47:13.110
Brian Greene, he did a great book called "The
Elegant Universe". He is writing the introduction

00:47:13.110 --> 00:47:16.160
of my book about the quantum psychics of ice
because it

