00:59:55.140 --> 01:00:08.000
&gt;&gt;Paul Miller: Right. It's the total flip
side of the capitalist economy. I mean, when

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:14.820
you think about our Western culture. We derive
value from scarcity and there's a really famous

01:00:14.820 --> 01:00:20.080
section of "Wealth of Nations" when Adam Smith
says, "Why is a diamond more expensive then

01:00:20.080 --> 01:00:25.720
water?" Water is precious to life when our
bodies are 92% water but why does somebody

01:00:25.720 --> 01:00:29.320
want some weird stone from the ground, you
know? I mean it's like people go to war over

01:00:29.320 --> 01:00:33.700
it, like diamonds and rubies. They'll raid
other villages because you know, if you're

01:00:33.700 --> 01:00:38.730
in Congo for example but water, which is precious
to everything we know, they're like, "Ugh,

01:00:38.730 --> 01:00:44.350
who cares?" you know? So the value of something
and the scarcity can always be, there's an

01:00:44.350 --> 01:00:50.180
eerie correlation and I can say the same thing
about cobalt for example in the Congo which

01:00:50.180 --> 01:00:54.150
is a very scarce metal and the same thing
is going on in China with what they call rare

01:00:54.150 --> 01:01:00.870
earths. The more rare something is, the more
we assign value to it and I'm giving a tiny

01:01:00.870 --> 01:01:06.350
Economics 101 here, but what I'm doing with
the idea of the "gift economy" is saying that

01:01:06.350 --> 01:01:10.441
it's about dematerialization of those values
and saying, "Wait a second. Let's think about

01:01:10.441 --> 01:01:15.440
social capital, cultural capital", which a
lot of people in the West are now studying

01:01:15.440 --> 01:01:19.430
rigorously. Pierre Bourdieu, who is a French
cultural theoretician, and there is an economist

01:01:19.430 --> 01:01:24.670
named Raj Patel who has a book called "The
Value of Nothing". It's a really great book

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:29.570
and Naomi Wolfe's whole theory of "Shock Doctrine"
and so on. There's a lot of people trying

01:01:29.570 --> 01:01:37.750
to question why scarcity. Why? The big why
with a capital W and I think there's something

01:01:37.750 --> 01:01:42.650
to be said for resetting the idea of values
and that's something I'm really interested

01:01:42.650 --> 01:01:48.200
in right now. I wouldn't say it's about storming
Wall Street and saying everything needs to

01:01:48.200 --> 01:01:52.340
be torn down because they're doing it themselves
anyway, you know? It's like, you know, the

01:01:52.340 --> 01:01:56.240
market system as we know with what they call
collateralized debt obligations and the futures

01:01:56.240 --> 01:02:03.620
market. Those are just what they call quantitative
methods of creating value out of nothing.

01:02:03.620 --> 01:02:10.990
I mean, the dollar, it's not based on any
specific gold or anything. It's just electronic

01:02:10.990 --> 01:02:17.230
values flying around, zeros and ones. So what
happens if our zeros and ones don't match

01:02:17.230 --> 01:02:22.980
the Vanuatuans zeroes and ones, you know?
I think we operate somewhere in the gap between

01:02:22.980 --> 01:02:26.180
those two economies.

